{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_inkster_ver01/data/sn88063294/00340589075/1945082201/0669.xml":{"full_text":"Markets Business\n10-C\nTHE DETROIT TIMES\nWhat's New\nIn Business\nPlastics to Arouse\nPublic Skepticism\nllv W ARD BCHI LTZ\nWith all the recent publicity\non plastic rats and cars with\nplastic bodies, it should lx* re*\nmembered that \u201cplastic\u201d is\nprobably the mo>t overexploited\nmaterial in exist wire today.\nGreedy manufacturers who\nrush to the marketplace with\ngaudy gadgets of plastic which\nare improperly engineered are\ngiving the resins a black eye\nwhich will take years to erase.\nOne of the properties of cer\ntain types of plastics which is\nfrequently ignored is the low\nmelting point. Three adven\ntures with handsome plastic\ngadgets for the home have\nconvinced me -of their worth\nlessness where the element of\nheat is present.\nFirst, a couple of years ago\nsome plastic clothespins were\ntried out and a few days in the\nsun left them twisted hope\nlessly out of shape.\nThe other day 1 took homp\nsome plastic holders for corn\non the cob. A single bout with\nhot corn and they looked like a\nglob of pull taffy.\nAnd a handsome looking plas\ntic water faucet strainer held\nup exactly one day\u2014then water\ncame streaming out its mis\nshapen sides.\nAs to automobiles,* plastic\nimpregnated with fibreglass may\nbe the answer, but one company\npresident tells me that it\u2019s im\npractical for big production\nbecause it requires too much\ntime to set in the mold.\nm\nPersonal Notes\nRichard O. Leongard has\nbeen named president of United\nChromium, Inc., of Detroit,\nwhile Theodore G. Coyle and\nHugh D. McLeesc were named\nxice presidents Fred L.\nrlunter of the Detroit office of\nAetna Life Insurance Co., was\nawarded a diploma for having\ncompleted the company\u2019s special\ninstruction course at the home\noffice in Hartford With the\nentry of the National Bank of\nDetroit into the personal loan\nfield, the linos are being drawn\nnow for a real battle for that\ntype business in this postwar\nera One motor company\nhere discharged every one hired\nafter May, 1941, with the oth\ners being let out subject to\nrecall Under existing tax\nJaws, some companies can actu\nally make more money in the\nnext couple of years by remain\ning closed, than they can by\noperating.\n\nReal Challange\nSweden is netting the jump on\nother nations in a drive for\nLatin-American markets. Busi\nness Week reports.\nFollowing the signing of a\nnew trade pact w-ith Argentina,\nStockholm traders, the maga\nzine says, have now made an\nagreement with Mexico by\nwhich Sweden will exchange\npaper and steel products for\nMexican cotton, petroleum and\nminerals.\nIn Chile, the Swedes are pur\nsuing a trading advantage de\nveloped during the war when\nthey created a special trading\nagency. Swedish Metal Indus\ntries, which created a sensation\nwith a locally-packaged razor\nblade, \u201cTops,\u201d and-sold large\nnumbers of streamlined bicycles\nat prices slightly lower than\nU. S. or British prewar lines.\nAnother popular Swedish prod\nuct in Chile is a special light\nweight sewing machine.\n\nBicycle Era Back\nAnd speaking of bikes, the\ngreat cycling \u00ab*ra o the Gay\nNineties will run a poor second\nto Americas bicycle enthusi\nasm, according to a postwar\nplanning study of the Eclipse\nMachine division of Bendix\nAviation Corp, a pioneer manu\nfacturer which went through\nthe earlier period and is draw\ning up production schedules to\nmeet accumulated demands\nafter victory.\nAmerican bicycle companies\nwill produce a record-smashing\ntotal of more than 2.000,000\nunits during the first year of\nunrestricted civilian production,\nsay officials of the com[>any,\nwhich makes coaster brakes.\nThis total will represent a sharp\nincrease over the 1,182,691 units\nproduced in 1899.\nOETROITWTIMES\nFuMUned every lA>eX D\u00bbr F*enln* and\nSundtyj Morning to tl.t Time* ruNtaMni\n>mpariy At 1-25 Hron Square, Detroit j