, S 2 50 bu\nPepper* cavenne 5. 1 $1 50 peck bkiket\nxr-en fan-y, S 2 50 bu No 1 SI 75-2\nbu hoi No 1 SI '1 25 btT red \u00bb\u00abee(.\nNo 1 SI 254 150 perk bkaket. pofgtoe*.\nNo 1 S 2 65 3 100-lb. \u00bbaek Radlahea\nred fanry SI dor: No 1 65 -65 dnj brh*\nVo* white Nn 1 74. dor b. hi Rut*\nbare* No 1 S 2 50\u00ab 7bu Rhubarb No 1\n6f>j?V dor bch* srjua*h Dalian fane*\ns3*4 7 bu N l 4 2 25,2.50 Table\nG'leen N\u2019e 1 44 5 bu aummer fanrt\nSI 40 bu N'. 1 S! 't 24 1. bu To\nmatoea, ou\u2019dor fancy $1 24 1 4 1 h ba\u00bbkf.\nNo 1 <3O\u00abSI 14 1b baakar Turnl;v\nbunched fancy $2 dor bch* No I Sl' rt\n125 topped, fancy, S 2 N 1 SI 2-\n1 40 bu\nEGGS\u2014 Firea targe *i\u00abs4 50-d>* rate.\nlar*\u00bb, 115 medium. $1443.\nAuto-\nGraphs\nPrice Decision Due\nOn Cars, Parts\nBs SILER FREEMAN\nDirts manufacturers arc cx\npf*cting something definite on\nthe price question out of Wash\nington this week, perhaps hy\ntomorrow. The automobile\n1 makers ate equally optimistic\nthat (>PA will announce some\nthing this week. The price\nquestion will be a groat hurdle\nlor the industry to get by.\nParts builders and suppliers\nare said 10 Iv in a better jxysi\ntion than the car manufac\nturers in the reconversion pic\nture. Only a few of them have\nbeen 100 i>er cent in war work.\nThe rest have been more or less\nin their familiar business and\ncan start making parts tomor\nrow, if the materials are made\navailable.\nThe situation is considered\nspotty but not pessimistic. Set\ntlement of the price question\nwill go a long way toward put\nting the suppliers hack in busi\nness quickly.\n41 la I\nTire Outlook Bright\nThe tire situation apj>ears\nbrighter too. While rationing\nis still continued, regulations\nare expected to be eased shortly\nand the entire tire rationing\nprogram abandoned in 45 to 60\ndays.\nTire manufacturers insist\nthey are in good shape and will\nbe ahead of the car builders\nwith a supply of passenger auto\nlires and tubes. They look for a\ni 33% per cent increase in small\nsize tires within 30 days and\nprewar rates will be reached by\nthe end of the year.\nTruck Program to End\nAnother rationing program\nthat is soon to go by the boards\nis that governing commercial ve\nhicles. With military trucks out\nof the way, the truck builders\ncan really go to town on the ci\nvilian items.\nThe Office of Defense Trans\nportation w ill go out of business\nwith the end of the truck ra\ntioning program. It has done a\nswell job in keeping the trans\nportation lines going throughout\nthe v\\ at.\nCar Casualties Gain\nThe number of cars going off\nthe road daily will be greatly\naccelerated hy the end of gaso\nline rationing. Although speed\nlimits are being observed fairly\nwell, the removal of the 35-mile\nlimit, never observed too stricl\nly, has caused many drivers to\nforget both the condition of\ntheir ear and tires, with the re\nsult that war-weary vehicles are\ngiving up more quickly than\nunder the rareful war regime.\nA Greyhound bus driver\ncounted seven ears with flat\ntires in one *hort stretch of\nroad.\nWarning on Aviation\nLoss of 5 per cent of the avia\ntion industry\u2019s assets during re\nconversion could wipe out work\ning capital and threaten the\nnation's chief source of security,\nEugene E. Wilson, president of\nthe Aircraft Industries Associa\ntion of America, declares in the\nSeptember issue of the maga\nzine Flying.\nThe need for careful planning\nof the contract termination\nprocess, he says, is critical for\nthe national weltare.\n\"We have had a long range\nprogram throughout the \\4ar.\u201d\nhe states. \u201cWe will have a long\nrange program In the future.\nWhat In vitally needed Is an Im\nmediate transition program\n44hirh alone ran preser\\e the\nexisting research and techno\nlogical skills (of the Industry).\u201d\nIngot\nDales Drop\nCLEVELAND, Aug. 21\u2014Steel\ningot operations for the week\nended Aug. 18 dropped about 28.5\npoints to 60 per cent, mainly a\nresult of the two-day Victory holi\nday on wUlnesday and Thursday.\nRates were difficult to estimate\nbecause of irregularities in pro\nduction and are subject to revision\nwhen actual figures ran be ob\ntained, according to the magazine\nSteel today.\nEstimated district rates were as\nfollows: Pittsburgh, 59 |mm- t ,-nt,\ndown L\u20197 [joints; Chicago, 72. down\n21; eastern Penn>ylvania, 77, down\n10; Wheeling. 65.5, down 32;\nYoungstown, 53, down 27; Cincin\nnati. 58, down 29; Birmingham.\n95. unchanged; Buffalo. 65, down\n16.5; New England. 84, down 2;\nSt. Louis, 50, down 18, Detroit, 60,\ndown !29\nDetroit Stocks\nSklk* N^t\nIn ion* High Low 12 4* Ch\nG\u00bbn Mtr* 225 l\nGraham Pal** 9 in io 10\nKlnx\u00bbton Prr.4 .10 l 4'\u2022 4\u2019* 4 1\nM CUiikhan O 1? 66 65 45 05\nMich Dl* Ck\u00bb 10 1 .3 3 3\nPackard 15 1 7 7 7\nParker Wol* \"4 l 17'i 17'* 17<i+- )i\nRlv Ratlin 22 4 5 5\nrdjrll\u2019e C\u00abrp 2 \u00bbX-\nU S Radiator 2 7', 7>* 7',\u2014\nDo r>fd 1 36 36 36- \u20146\nWayne scr Pr Jfl 1 6 4\nUNLISTED\nAmer M 40 1 20 20 20 \u20141\nAnaconda 100 1 31 31 31\nAviation Cp 10 3 7', 7\u2019* 7',\u2014\nI I 1W\nCuftlaa-Wrliht 2 V-. 41. 51,-1,\nNatl Auto f I Sera 1 13\u00bb, 13*, 17\u00bb, *1\nN Y Tent 150 3 2 3 2 3 2 3\nPen RR 1 00 1 34 34 .74 \u20143\nSo~'nv V-r 40 2 14', I*4* 14S\u2014 >4\nDtildend* In 4he (nr*f\u00bblni table are the\namnunta paid nr parable an far thla year.\nEarnings\nBI N* FICI At isnt NTimi LOAN fORr\nr- \u25a0nd Junr 30 104 s 1*44\nN-< pt 4- 42 2 4'. 344 S 2 065 71 2\nCommon thare earnltt** SI 0.7 04c\nfttott I*4 rxy t*C.\n2\u00ab wk* end July 14 1045 1444\nNet pi fit f 436 74J $604 173\n1 Common ahare tarnlas* II OS *4*\nBlueprints lor Posfwar America\nAccurate Market\nPreilictions Difficult\n(FDITOirS NOTH: IP. IP. Cumberland, investment\nbanker, today nets as guest columnist for Merryle Stanley\nRukeyser, uho is on ration. Tomorrow Asa l\\ Call,\npresident of the Pacific Mutual Life Insura nee Co, of Los\nAngeles, irill write about the problems of the Pacific\nCoast in the postwar period.)\nBy W. W. CUMBERLAND\nInvestment Banker\nCertain things are supposed to be self-evident, such as that\npurchasing power\u201d maktfs prosperity\u2019, that control of prices\ncan prevent inflation, that government planning will avoid a\npostwar depression and that huge increases of money and\nbank deposits compel some sort of proportional advance in the\nprices of stocks. Or are these self-evident?\nIt is well to examine the generally accepted doctrine that\ncontinued government deficits, with corresponding increases\nin bank deposits are a virtual guarantee of rising prices for\nequities. Like so many other things in economics\u2014it depends.\nFurthermore, government planners and business economists\nalike have been sadly inaccurate in stating the time when pre\ndicted events will take place.\n9\nCites Danger in Overabundance of Money\nFor example, a fairly safe generalization is that additions to\nthe money supply without comparable additions to the supply of\ngoods result in higher commodity prices. Yet various devices can\ndefer the exported effect until the cause may have been forgotten.\nIf unrestricted issuance of currency and credit would make\nthe world rich, by bringing about high wages, high prices for farm\nproducts and other Benefits which add up to an improved national\nstandard of living, then all countries would he wealthy.\nWhen the European war broke out in 1939, commercial bank\ndeposits were less ihan $60,000,000,000. Now they stand at ap\nproximately $128,000,000,000. Currency \u00bbn circulation at the out\nbreak of the war was about $7.500.0(H).000, as compared with the\ncurrent figures of $26,500,000,000. Meanwhile, the public debt has\nincreased from approximately $16,000,000,000 to a present level of\n$262,000,000,000.\n4t\nStocks Failed to Show Great Spurt Upward\nIf the simple theory were valid that greater deficits and more\nmoney and credit are synonymous with higher prices for equities,\nthe stock market should haVe shown enormous bouyancy through\nout this period.\nActually, however, the Dow-Jonos average of industrial stocks\nreached approximately 156 a few weeks after the outbreak of the\nEuropean war. and at present this average is around 161. Thu\nafter six years this standard index of industrial equities is at\nabout the same level as at the beginning of the period, and at no\npoint has it stood substantially higher. This is in spite of bigger\nand better deficits, unprecedented bank deposits and money in\ncirculation beyond all previous ex|>crirnce in this country.\n4r\nIndustrial List Fell Approximately 40 Per Cent\nIn the interval, moreover, industrial stocks fell approximately\n40 per cent below the peak of 1939, and this occurred while deficits,\nbank deposits and currency were all showing huge increases and\nwhile the yield on high grade bonds was constantly declining.\nTherefore there is no simple system of determining stork\nprices, nor can a trend in the market be safely predicated on this\nor that extraneous development.\nPrices for stocks are the end figures which emerge as the\nresultant of such diverse factors as the w'eather, social develop\nments, political organization, international events and a complex\nof thousands of additional and constantly changing items. This is\nwhat makes it so difficult to forecast with accuracy the prices of\nstocks and also what makes the attempt so fascinating.\n\nEarnings Dependent on Government Tax Policy\nIn general, stocks sell in some rough relation to actual and\nprospective earnings. Such earnings, however, are far more de\npendent upon tax policies of government, labor relations, war or\npeace, boom or depression, and many other factors than they are\non the magnitude of hank deposits or currency in circulation.\nOnly when an increase in money and cred't occurs at a more\nrapid rate than advances in commodity prices, wages and other\nindustrial costs do money factors tend toward bringing about\nhigher stock prices When taxes or labor costs are such that\nnet corporate profits decline, there ran be and frequently arc\nfalling stock markets while bank deposits are rapidlv expanding.\n4t\nYield on High Grade Bonds Lowest in History\nNor are low interest rates an adequate reason for being cer\ntain that stocks will advance. It is enough to recall that in 1937\nand 1938 the price of industrial stocks was cut in two, while the\nyield on high grade bonds in 1937 was the lowest theretofore at\ntained in American history and was still lower in 1938.\nNot in money factors but in profitable production under re\nliable political and social conditions must the cause be sought of\na buoyant stock market. Increasing bank deposits, based on ex\npanding economy, are properly rellected in greater values for\nequities.\nRising stock prices may or may not accompany enlarged bank\ndeposits which merely represent financial disorder, and if any\nadvance occurs it represents disease, not prosperity.\n'Fibre' Holders\nConvert Stock\nHolders of 155.920 of the 200,-\n000 shares of National Automotive\nF'ibres, Inc., 6 per cent $lO par\npreferred stock previously out\nstanding have converted into com\nmon stock, according to J. H.\nGrut, secretary-treasurer.\nThe conversion offer, which was\nannounced June 27. was on a\nshare for share basis, and expired\nAug. 11. The remaining preferred\nshares will be redeemed Sept. 1 at\n$11.50 a share plus accrued divi\ndend of 15 cents a share.\nA 15-eent dividend is also pay\nable Sept. 15 to common stock\nholders.\nPlants of the company are pres\nently being prepared for the re\nturn to peacetime operations and\nit is expected that production of\ninterior trim will be attained in\ntime to meet the delivery sched\nules of the company's automobile\ncustomers.\nHint Shoe Rationing\nTo End in 2 Months\nWASHINGTON. Aug. 21-Shoe\nrationing is expected to end in\ntwo months at the outside and\nmay be lifted within two weeks,\naccording to a survey of the War\nProduction Board and the Office\nof Price Administration. Com\npletion of the supply and produc\ntion statistics apparently is the\nonly thing delaying it.\nIndustry to Need\n54 Million Workers\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 21\u2014Ci\nvilian goods production will aggre\ngate .ssn.sl\u00df,ooo,o<to a year by\nSeptember, 1946. and provide jobs\nfor 54 million workers, the Com\nmittee for Economic Development\npredicted today.\nCredit Curbs\nSeen Eased\nWASHINGTON, Aug. 21-Con\nsumer credit controls may be\neased under plans being studied\nby the government. First to go\nprobablv will be the control exer\ncised by the Federal Reserve\nBoard over charge accounts.\nThe board is expected, however,\nto retain control over terms for\ninstalment buying.\nIndustrial Bank\nVotes 75c Dividend\nThe Industrial National Bank\nof Detroit has' declared a dividend\nof 75 cents, payable August 31 to\nholders of record August 21,\nSTRUCK\nsl2 Of. for t $.16 Hsfor3 \"Hande*\nAndy nat. adv. Thousands in u\u00bb.\nSameday *hip f>x2rub. trd whl* Roll\nI rap 44'ht. 14'no*e. Wt.\n128 It* For aII purp lOda Unrated\nL firm*ca*h. Full Ruar f ob. Writ* for\nI* quant, discounts. Order from\nj HANDFFS CO 51 0\nJ .n*IWIU tu. Rleominqtnn Ml.\n1\nI\ni. A\nZ9E\nBUSINESS\nLOANS\nQUICK SERVICE\nUNION INVESTMENT CO.\n310 Knrt Sire* Hml\n(Berry 7474\nDETROIT MANUFACTURING\nCORPORATION\nExpanding for postwar\nproduct for domestic\nand industrial use with\npotential sales of over\n$3,000,000 per year. Sell\ning 49% of stock in com\npany for $245,000. Pri\nvate sales of stock only\nfrom owner.\nWrit* Box Numbor B-248\nDetroit Time*. Detroit JI, Mick.\nMarkefShows\nMixed Tone\nNEW YORK. Aur. 21 (UP'i\nThe stock market turned highly\nirregular in the late morning\ndealings today after a firm start.\nTrading lightened to a pace of\naround 1.000,000 shares for a full\nsession.\nSelective selling went ahead in\nmany issues and some of the high\npriced stocks encountered air\npockets that dropped their prices\nas much as four